==English==

===Pronunciation===
*frā, /freɪ/, /<tt>freI</tt>/
*:[[Rhymes:English:-eɪ|Rhymes: -eɪ]]

===Noun===
'''fray''' (plural '''frays''')

#[[Affray]]; [[broil]]; [[contest]]; [[combat]]; [[brawl]]; [[melee]].
#:"O me!  What '''fray''' was here?"  -Shakespeare ''(Romeo and Juliet)''

===Translations===
*Hebrew: קטטה (ktata) תחרות (tacharut)

===Verb===
'''fray''', '''frayed''', '''fraying''', '''frays'''
#to [[unravel]]. Used particularly for the edge of something made of [[cloth]], or the end of a [[rope]].
#:''The ribbon frayed at the cut end.''
# (figurative) to cause exhaustion, wear out (a person's mental strength)
#: ''The stressful day ended in frayed nerves.'' (Metaphorical use; nerves are visualised as strings)

